First Read: 31-Mar-26
HJR301 Enrolled
1 Enrolled, An Act,
2
3 ESTABLISHING THE ALABAMA FOREST PRODUCTS RETENTION
4 AND PULP AND PAPER MILL STABILITY STUDY COMMISSION.
5
6 WHEREAS, the forestry industry is a cornerstone of
7 Alabama's economy, with over 23 million acres of forestland
8 covering roughly 69 percent of the state; and
9 WHEREAS, the forestry industry also generates a
10 total annual economic impact of 36 billion dollars to, and
11 directly supports over 40,000 jobs in, this state; and
12 WHEREAS, Alabama is home to more than 110
13 manufacturing facilities, including critical sawmills and
14 pulp and paper mills, all of which are crucial for rural
15 economies and economic development; and
16 WHEREAS, the pulp and paper sector of the forestry
17 industry is facing evolving market challenges, international
18 competition, and environmental regulatory changes that
19 necessitate a proactive approach to keeping these facilities
20 in Alabama; and
21 WHEREAS, it is in the state's best interest to
22 ensure that pulp and paper mills located in the state remain
23 competitive, well-capitalized, and operational to sustain
24 local economies, forestry jobs, and ancillary service jobs;
25 now therefore,
26 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
27 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That the Alabama Forest Products
28 Retention and Pulp and Paper Mill Stability Study Commission
Page 1

Retention and Pulp and Paper Mill Stability Study Commission
HJR301 Enrolled
29 is established to study the forestry industry as a whole,
30 with a specific focus on the best practices to retain pulp
31 and paper mills in this state and how best to maintain the
32 state's attractiveness to these sectors.
33 (a) The study commission shall consist of the
34 following members:
35 (1) Each member of the Agriculture and Forestry
36 Committee of the House of Representatives, with the chair of
37 the committee serving as chair of the study commission.
38 (2) One member of the House of Representatives,
39 appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
40 (3) One member of the Senate, appointed by the
41 Lieutenant Governor.
42 (4) The State Forester, or his or her designee.
43 (5) The Secretary of Commerce, or his or her
44 designee.
45 (6) One member appointed by the Alabama Forestry
46 Association.
47 (7) One member appointed by the Economic Development
48 Partnership of Alabama.
49 (8) One member appointed by Manufacture Alabama.
50 (b) The appointing authorities shall coordinate
51 their appointments to assure the study commission membership
52 is inclusive and reflects the racial, gender, geographic,
53 urban, rural, and economic diversity of the state.
54 (c) The initial meeting of the study commission
55 shall be held at the call of the chair no later than July 1,
56 2026. The study commission may then meet as necessary to
Page 2

2026. The study commission may then meet as necessary to
HJR301 Enrolled
57 conduct business.
58 (d) The study commission shall assess all of the
59 following matters:
60 (1) Strategies to retain forest products and pulp
61 and paper mills in the state, including methods of
62 encouraging existing pulp and paper mills to maintain and
63 expand their presence in the state.
64 (2) Infrastructure needs of pulp and paper mills in
65 the state, including available resources and energy
66 infrastructure needed for mill operation.
67 (3) Methods by which state environmental, labor, and
68 tax policies may be revised to ensure a pro-growth
69 environment for the pulp and paper sectors.
70 (4) Current transitions in the pulp and paper
71 products market and how the state may attract emerging
72 paper-based technology manufacturing.
73 (e) The study commission shall prepare and submit a
74 comprehensive report of its findings, conclusions, and
75 recommendations for proposed legislation, if any, to the
76 Legislature not later than November 1, 2026, at which point
77 the study commission shall stand dissolved.
78 (f)(1) The legislative members of the study
79 commission shall be entitled to their legislative
80 compensation, per diem, and travel expenses for each day
81 they attend a meeting of the study commission pursuant to
82 Section 49 of the Constitution of Alabama of 2022.
83
84
